All right.

00:00:05.220 --> 00:00:06.980
Welcome, everybody.

00:00:06.980 --> 00:00:08.260
I'm Taylor Wilson.

00:00:08.260 --> 00:00:09.760
For those of you
who know who I am,

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:12.190
I'm a nuclear physicist
in my day job.

00:00:12.190 --> 00:00:14.830
I built a nuclear
reactor when I was 14.

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:16.510
I think that's one
of the many things

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:19.570
that we share in common
our interests in things

00:00:19.570 --> 00:00:21.320
of that nature when
we were really young.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:24.250
So I'm excited to be here
today to interview Dr. Kaku

00:00:24.250 --> 00:00:27.190
about physics and the future.

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:30.670
So I guess with that
we'll get started.

00:00:30.670 --> 00:00:33.780
I will say that when we
finish our talking up here,

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:35.780
we're going to take
questions from the audience.

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:39.700
So if you want to start thinking
about some questions that you

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:43.720
have for Dr. Kaku about the
future of humanity or physics,

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:45.670
we're happy to try to
give you an answer.

00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:49.128
So with that, thank you for
joining us this morning.

00:00:49.128 --> 00:00:50.170
MICHIO KAKU: My pleasure.

00:00:50.170 --> 00:00:50.962
TAYLOR WILSON: Yes.

00:00:50.962 --> 00:00:54.352
I wanted to start with something
that's been in the news

00:00:54.352 --> 00:00:56.560
the last couple of weeks
and I'm sure a lot of people

00:00:56.560 --> 00:00:57.602
are really interested in.

00:00:57.602 --> 00:01:00.700
And that's that picture of
a black hole that was taken

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:02.115
by the Event Horizon telescope.

00:01:02.115 --> 00:01:03.490
Maybe you could
talk a little bit

00:01:03.490 --> 00:01:06.170
about how you feel
seeing that image

00:01:06.170 --> 00:01:10.610
and what that tells us about
the physics of the universe.

00:01:10.610 --> 00:01:15.040
MICHIO KAKU: Well, when I was
a grad student at Berkeley,

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:18.110
black holes were
considered science fiction.

00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:21.340
It was considered like
finding a unicorn.

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:22.960
It's a fabled animal.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:24.830
Everyone talks about unicorns.

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:28.000
But no one's ever seen one
because they don't exist.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.380
Now we've got it in the bag.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:32.540
We've actually photographed
the silhouette,

00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:35.030
the shadow of a black hole.

00:01:35.030 --> 00:01:37.460
But that's just the beginning.

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:41.830
You see, this black hole is
spinning, spinning rapidly.

00:01:41.830 --> 00:01:45.610
We've clocked black holes at
about a million miles an hour.

00:01:45.610 --> 00:01:48.670
And if you look at
Einstein's equations

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:53.800
and have a spinning black hole,
they don't collapse to a dot.

00:01:53.800 --> 00:01:58.060
They collapse to a ring,
a ring of neutrons.

00:01:58.060 --> 00:02:01.910
So it's that centrifugal force
prevents it from collapsing.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:03.100
It's stable.

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:07.270
If you were to fall through
the north pole of the ring,

00:02:07.270 --> 00:02:11.350
you wind up, mathematically,
on a parallel universe.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:14.440
And if you go a second
time, you wind up

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:16.780
on another parallel universe.

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:19.270
And you keep on going
through the ring.

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:21.430
It's like going through
an apartment building,

00:02:21.430 --> 00:02:27.040
hitting the elevator, each
floor being another universe.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:29.500
And we want to
know is that real,

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:33.490
or is it just a mathematical
fiction, a unicorn,

00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:36.670
in other words, a
wormhole at the center

00:02:36.670 --> 00:02:39.460
of a spinning black hole.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:43.080
And that's what we want to
do with the next generation

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:45.340
of radio telescope technology.

00:02:45.340 --> 00:02:46.090
TAYLOR WILSON: OK.

00:02:46.090 --> 00:02:46.930
That's fascinating.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:51.400
So this idea that black holes,
40, 50 years ago were something

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:53.950
that we might have had
theoretical evidence

00:02:53.950 --> 00:02:56.110
of or even indirect
observational

00:02:56.110 --> 00:03:00.640
evidence of, but now we have
that real, first, true, direct

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:02.050
observational evidence of.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:04.990
So what you're saying
is maybe what's next--

00:03:04.990 --> 00:03:09.427
what could those other
possibilities be for objects

00:03:09.427 --> 00:03:10.510
that we have not yet seen.

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:11.302
MICHIO KAKU: Right.

00:03:11.302 --> 00:03:14.980
In other words, a black hole
is a cosmic roach motel.

00:03:14.980 --> 00:03:18.730
Everything checks in,
nothing checks out.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:21.160
But then the question
is, where does it go?

00:03:21.160 --> 00:03:24.970
Where does all that stuff go
if it falls into a black hole?

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:27.880
Some theorists have
stated that maybe it's

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:31.300
blown out the other
end as a white hole.

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:35.350
So maybe there's a white hole on
the other side of a black hole

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:37.287
such that it spews out matter.

00:03:37.287 --> 00:03:38.120
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:41.980
MICHIO KAKU: Now doesn't
that sound like the big bang?

00:03:41.980 --> 00:03:45.340
Some people even think
that maybe our universe

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:49.240
is a white hole and
that we are connected

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.205
with an umbilical cord
to another universe.

00:03:52.205 --> 00:03:53.330
TAYLOR WILSON: Fascinating.

00:03:53.330 --> 00:03:55.270
MICHIO KAKU: This is
the multiverse idea

00:03:55.270 --> 00:03:57.550
which is now gaining
a tremendous amount

00:03:57.550 --> 00:03:59.830
of theoretical credibility.

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.772
Though, of course, we have not
yet proven this theory at all.

00:04:02.772 --> 00:04:04.480
TAYLOR WILSON: Well,
that's a good segue,

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:07.622
talking about multiverses
and into something

00:04:07.622 --> 00:04:09.580
that you're quite familiar
with, string theory.

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:10.997
So maybe you want
to tell everyone

00:04:10.997 --> 00:04:14.350
kind of your background and
how you ended up in physics.

00:04:14.350 --> 00:04:16.387
You're from this area
originally, correct?

00:04:16.387 --> 00:04:17.470
MICHIO KAKU: That's right.

00:04:17.470 --> 00:04:18.829
I'm a local kid.

00:04:18.829 --> 00:04:20.680
I was born in San Jose.

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:24.880
I grew up in Palo
Alto, went to school,

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:27.100
up to high school in Palo Alto.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:29.620
But when I was eight
years old, when

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:31.750
I was eight years old
something happened

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:34.630
which changed my whole destiny.

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:37.570
And that is in the
newspapers they

00:04:37.570 --> 00:04:41.370
announced that a great
scientist had just died.

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:45.850
And they put a picture of
his desk on the front page.

00:04:45.850 --> 00:04:51.790
And the caption said this
is the unfinished manuscript

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:55.330
from the greatest
scientist of our time.

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:58.810
And I thought to myself,
why couldn't he finish it?

00:04:58.810 --> 00:05:03.200
What's so hard that a
great scientist could not

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:04.590
finish this theory?

00:05:04.590 --> 00:05:06.290
It's a homework problem, right?

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:08.300
Why didn't he ask his mother?

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:10.460
What could be so hard?

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:12.090
So I went to the library.

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:17.150
I found that this man's
name was Albert Einstein.

00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:20.270
And that book, that
book on the desk

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:24.440
was the unfinished
theory of everything.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:27.290
He wanted an equation
one inch long

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:32.360
that would allow him to
quote, "read the mind of God."

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:34.790
So I said to myself, wow.

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:35.457
That's for me.

00:05:35.457 --> 00:05:36.290
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:38.082
MICHIO KAKU: That's
what I want to work on.

00:05:38.082 --> 00:05:42.170
I want to help finish this great
theory that Einstein could not

00:05:42.170 --> 00:05:42.860
finish.

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:45.350
Well, today, we
think we have it.

00:05:45.350 --> 00:05:46.940
It's called string theory.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:49.400
It has not yet been tested.

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:53.660
But we think that this
could be the final unicorn,

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:57.170
the final theory of everything.

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:00.350
So that every
neutron, every proton,

00:06:00.350 --> 00:06:03.740
every electron is nothing
but tiny vibrations

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:05.420
on a tiny string.

00:06:05.420 --> 00:06:06.950
This is an electron.

00:06:06.950 --> 00:06:08.240
That's a quark.

00:06:08.240 --> 00:06:09.950
This is a neutrino.

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:12.620
Nothing but musical
notes on a string.

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:15.860
Physics, therefore,
is the harmonies

00:06:15.860 --> 00:06:17.960
you can write on a string.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:23.300
Chemistry is the melodies you
can play on vibrating strings.

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:27.300
The universe is a
symphony of strings.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:31.590
And then the mind of
God, the mind of God

00:06:31.590 --> 00:06:35.490
that Einstein wrote about for
the last 30 years of his life,

00:06:35.490 --> 00:06:41.970
the mind of God is cosmic
music resonating through 11

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:43.322
dimensional hyperspace.

00:06:43.322 --> 00:06:44.280
TAYLOR WILSON: Amazing.

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:46.440
MICHIO KAKU: That
is the mind of God.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.260
TAYLOR WILSON: So this idea,
this grand unified theory

00:06:49.260 --> 00:06:52.650
that's based on
string theory, is

00:06:52.650 --> 00:06:55.197
something you've spent your
entire career working on?

00:06:55.197 --> 00:06:56.280
MICHIO KAKU: That's right.

00:06:56.280 --> 00:06:58.710
We want that equation
one inch long.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:02.130
Now for strings, not membranes,
but just for strings,

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:03.047
we have that equation.

00:07:03.047 --> 00:07:03.838
TAYLOR WILSON: Yes.

00:07:03.838 --> 00:07:05.250
MICHIO KAKU: That's my equation.

00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:07.590
I'm the co-founder of
string field theory, which

00:07:07.590 --> 00:07:10.950
allows you to summarize
this vast body of knowledge

00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:12.990
into an equation one inch long.

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:16.350
But today we have
membranes, M-theory, which

00:07:16.350 --> 00:07:18.280
makes things more complicated.

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:19.960
So it's unfinished.

00:07:19.960 --> 00:07:22.920
So if one of you in the
audience ever figures out

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:25.840
the final theory, be
sure to tell me first.

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:27.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.460
We'll split the
Nobel Prize together.

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:31.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:34.530
TAYLOR WILSON: Now that's
not a bad deal for you.

00:07:34.530 --> 00:07:35.920
That's really interesting.

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:38.490
So this is the idea of taking
the physics [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:42.390
large, like, the laws
that govern gravitation

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:45.600
and the like, and unifying
it with the theories that

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:47.500
govern the very small
and the very hot,

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:49.780
the quantum rules
of the universe.

00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:51.780
So your idea is
that the best way

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:53.997
to solve this problem is
through string theory?

00:07:53.997 --> 00:07:55.080
MICHIO KAKU: That's right.

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:58.200
Nature has a left
hand and a right hand.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:01.200
The left hand, as you said, is
the theory of the very big--

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.950
black holes, the big bang,
Einstein's theory of gravity.

00:08:04.950 --> 00:08:08.820
But the other hand of God
is the quantum theory,

00:08:08.820 --> 00:08:10.500
the theory of the very small.

00:08:10.500 --> 00:08:14.310
So why should we have
two hands that don't

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:16.230
coordinate with each other.

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:18.647
And that's why we do believe
that there is a final theory.

00:08:18.647 --> 00:08:19.438
TAYLOR WILSON: Yes.

00:08:19.438 --> 00:08:21.360
MICHIO KAKU: And we're
going to test it.

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:25.650
The Large Hadron Collider has
given us the Higgs Boson, given

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:27.540
us the so-called God particle.

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:31.740
But now, we're going to build
a successor to the Large Hadron

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:32.789
Collider.

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:36.299
The Japanese, with the
International Linear Collider,

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:38.880
the Chinese with the
Circular Collider,

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:42.350
and the European Union--

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:46.140
three ventures have been
proposed for the successor

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.790
of the Large Hadron Collider.

00:08:47.790 --> 00:08:51.120
But unfortunately, not
from the United States.

00:08:51.120 --> 00:08:52.807
We're left in the
dust once again.

00:08:52.807 --> 00:08:53.640
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:55.440
But that's the
way to really test

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:57.660
the theory is to build
a very large collider,

00:08:57.660 --> 00:09:00.420
collide the particles,
and see what comes out.

00:09:00.420 --> 00:09:04.380
MICHIO KAKU: Our super collider
was canceled in the 1990s

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:07.080
to be built outside
Dallas, Texas.

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:11.140
One reason why it was canceled
is because a congressman asked

00:09:11.140 --> 00:09:14.640
a physicist on the last
days of hearing quote,

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:18.630
"Will we find God
with your machine?

00:09:18.630 --> 00:09:21.580
If so, I will change my vote."

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:25.200
Well, the physicists
didn't know what to say.

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:29.100
$10 billion to find God--

00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:32.730
so he said, we're going
to find the Higgs boson.

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:36.510
Well, all the jaws hit the floor
in the United States Congress.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:41.760
$10 billion for another
goddamn subatomic particle.

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:43.980
They took the vote,
and it was canceled.

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:48.040
Since then we physicists
had to ask ourselves,

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:50.448
how would we answer
that question?

00:09:50.448 --> 00:09:51.240
TAYLOR WILSON: Yes.

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:52.657
MICHIO KAKU: The
next time someone

00:09:52.657 --> 00:09:56.010
asks us will we find
God with your machine,

00:09:56.010 --> 00:09:57.493
how will we answer it?

00:09:57.493 --> 00:09:58.410
TAYLOR WILSON: Mm-hmm.

00:09:58.410 --> 00:10:01.800
MICHIO KAKU: I would have
answered it differently.

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:07.320
I would have said God, by
whatever signs or symbols you

00:10:07.320 --> 00:10:12.240
ascribe to the deity, this
machine, the Super Collider

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:16.890
will take us as close as
humanly possible to his greatest

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:20.010
creation, genesis.

00:10:20.010 --> 00:10:22.890
This is a genesis machine.

00:10:22.890 --> 00:10:26.910
It will recreate, on a small
scale, the most incredible

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:32.040
event in the history of
the universe, its birth.

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:34.890
Unfortunately, we
said Higgs boson.

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:36.378
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:36.378 --> 00:10:37.670
TAYLOR WILSON: Not as exciting.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:38.813
MICHIO KAKU: Wrong answer.

00:10:38.813 --> 00:10:39.980
TAYLOR WILSON: Wrong answer.

00:10:39.980 --> 00:10:43.257
And you have a little personal
experience with colliders.

00:10:43.257 --> 00:10:45.590
Maybe you want to talk a
little bit about what you built

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:46.940
when you were in high school?

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:47.690
MICHIO KAKU: Yeah.

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:51.800
Well, just like you, when I
was a junior in Cubberley High

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:54.800
School, which is just
about two miles from here,

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:58.790
I decided to build a particle
accelerator, an atom smasher,

00:10:58.790 --> 00:11:01.190
in my mom's garage.

00:11:01.190 --> 00:11:03.410
So I went to my mom,
and I said, mom,

00:11:03.410 --> 00:11:06.800
can I have permission
to build a 2.3 million

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:11.190
electron volt betatron electron
accelerator in the garage?

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:16.470
And she kind of looked
at me and said, sure.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:17.360
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:18.580
MICHIO KAKU: Why not?

00:11:18.580 --> 00:11:20.350
And don't forget to
take out the garbage.

00:11:20.350 --> 00:11:21.740
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:23.630
MICHIO KAKU: So I
went to Westinghouse.

00:11:23.630 --> 00:11:26.285
I got 400 pounds of
transformer steel.

00:11:26.285 --> 00:11:29.810
I went to Varian, got
22 miles of copper wire.

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:32.090
And on the football
field over Christmas,

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:34.478
we [INAUDIBLE] 22
miles of copper wire.

00:11:34.478 --> 00:11:35.270
TAYLOR WILSON: Wow.

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:37.150
MICHIO KAKU: It
finally was finished.

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:40.580
It consumed six
kilowatts of power.

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:43.467
I would plug it in,
I closed my ears.

00:11:43.467 --> 00:11:44.300
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:46.175
MICHIO KAKU: And I heard
this crackling sound

00:11:46.175 --> 00:11:49.280
as all this energy surged
in the capacitor bank.

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:51.560
And then I heard this
pop, pop, pop sound

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:54.960
as I blew out all the
fuses in my mom's house.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:56.103
TAYLOR WILSON: Yeah.

00:11:56.103 --> 00:11:58.520
MICHIO KAKU: The whole house
would be plunged in darkness.

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:03.190
And my poor mom, she must have
said to herself, why couldn't I

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:07.330
have a son who plays basketball?

