00:24:56.590 --> 00:24:59.680
that opened the door
to faster than light

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:03.400
travel when he
introduced the wormhole.

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:07.270
That was the first paper
written about wormholes.

00:25:07.270 --> 00:25:11.440
The first book about wormholes
was written in the 1800s

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:15.280
by Charles Dodgson,
Oxford mathematician who

00:25:15.280 --> 00:25:19.750
wrote a children's book,
"Alice in Wonderland."

00:25:19.750 --> 00:25:22.030
Now this Oxford
mathematician could not

00:25:22.030 --> 00:25:24.340
write under his name,
Charles Dodgson.

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:25.930
It was a children's book.

00:25:25.930 --> 00:25:29.650
So he wrote under a pen
name, Lewis Carroll.

00:25:29.650 --> 00:25:33.070
But the looking glass
is the wormhole.

00:25:33.070 --> 00:25:35.800
You put your hand through
the looking glass,

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:39.850
and you wind up on a
different space and time.

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:43.690
So we think that, yes, that
would be a way to go faster

00:25:43.690 --> 00:25:45.770
than the speed of light.

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:47.480
Now, what's the catch?

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:49.550
There's always a
catch some place.

00:25:49.550 --> 00:25:53.290
First of all, the energy
necessary to punch

00:25:53.290 --> 00:25:57.820
a hole in space and time
is that of a black hole.

00:25:57.820 --> 00:26:01.030
You're talking about
fantastic amounts of energy.

00:26:01.030 --> 00:26:03.370
Second, you have
to stabilize it.

00:26:03.370 --> 00:26:05.470
That means negative energy.

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:08.500
Positive energy to open
the gateway, and then

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:11.185
negative energy to prevent
it from collapsing,

00:26:11.185 --> 00:26:13.560
in other words, stability.

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:16.760
And this has not
yet been worked out.

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:20.670
It would take a very advanced
civilization to do this.

00:26:20.670 --> 00:26:25.460
Now I'm on radio and I
broadcast every week.

00:26:25.460 --> 00:26:27.890
And some people call
me on the telephone.

00:26:27.890 --> 00:26:31.370
And they say professor,
you're wrong.

00:26:31.370 --> 00:26:32.810
You're totally wrong.

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:36.620
The aliens aren't there in
outer space with warp drive.

00:26:36.620 --> 00:26:40.160
The aliens are
here on the Earth.

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:42.620
And then I ask them,
how do you know?

00:26:42.620 --> 00:26:44.960
And they say, well,
they've been kidnapped,

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:46.670
kidnapped by flying saucers.

00:26:46.670 --> 00:26:48.770
They know that
they're out there.

00:26:48.770 --> 00:26:50.750
Well I have a word of advice.

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:56.180
The next time you are kidnapped
by a flying saucer, for God's

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:57.545
sake, steal something.

00:26:57.545 --> 00:26:59.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:59.500 --> 00:27:03.252
There's no law against stealing
from an extraterrestrial

00:27:03.252 --> 00:27:03.835
civilization--

00:27:03.835 --> 00:27:05.210
TAYLOR WILSON:
That's true, yeah.

00:27:05.210 --> 00:27:06.890
MICHIO KAKU: --no
law whatsoever.

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:12.750
An alien ship, an alien hammer,
an alien paperclip, anything

00:27:12.750 --> 00:27:16.453
so that you have bragging rights
about going into outer space.

00:27:16.453 --> 00:27:17.870
TAYLOR WILSON:
That's good advice.

00:27:17.870 --> 00:27:19.170
It's good advice.

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:19.670
All right.

00:27:19.670 --> 00:27:22.490
I guess we can start
opening it up to questions.

00:27:22.490 --> 00:27:26.150
If you want to make your way
to the mic, start to line up.

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:29.350
We'll try to do our best to
answer the questions that you

00:27:29.350 --> 00:27:29.850
have.

00:27:29.850 --> 00:27:32.310
So over here, you
were the first.

00:27:32.310 --> 00:27:33.320
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:27:33.320 --> 00:27:35.510
Dr. Kaku, thank you so
much for coming out.

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:36.620
I'm really inspired.

00:27:36.620 --> 00:27:41.000
I wanted to hear some of your
thoughts on ethical development

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:44.210
and how we might be able to
help machines uphold ethics

00:27:44.210 --> 00:27:45.895
in our society.

00:27:45.895 --> 00:27:47.270
MICHIO KAKU: What
was that again?

00:27:47.270 --> 00:27:50.630
TAYLOR WILSON: Ethics and how we
help machines uphold the ethics

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:51.950
that we as a society hold.

00:27:51.950 --> 00:27:54.000
Is that correct?

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:55.740
MICHIO KAKU: Well,
several things--

00:27:55.740 --> 00:27:57.920
first of all, we
have to make sure

00:27:57.920 --> 00:28:05.100
that this technology is used by
the largest numbers of people.

00:28:05.100 --> 00:28:08.610
But you see when technology
first becomes available,

00:28:08.610 --> 00:28:10.370
it's always for the rich.

00:28:10.370 --> 00:28:14.510
When the telephone first
came out over 100 years ago,

00:28:14.510 --> 00:28:16.790
who had personal telephones?

00:28:16.790 --> 00:28:18.230
It was rich people.

00:28:18.230 --> 00:28:21.920
But eventually, we have things
like Moore's law, computer

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:24.240
power doubling every 18 months.

00:28:24.240 --> 00:28:28.190
And so with time, the cost
of telephone goes down.

00:28:28.190 --> 00:28:32.240
We once thought there was going
to be a digital divide when

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:37.910
rich people would have laptops,
poor people would have nothing.

00:28:37.910 --> 00:28:39.890
But now we know
that most children

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:42.260
are the first to be wired up.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:44.930
Because if a child is
not on the internet,

00:28:44.930 --> 00:28:47.640
they don't exist
on the internet.

00:28:47.640 --> 00:28:49.850
But there's also
another ethical problem

00:28:49.850 --> 00:28:52.190
for the next coming decades.

00:28:52.190 --> 00:28:56.990
Some people wonder, when robots
become smarter and smarter,

00:28:56.990 --> 00:29:00.100
are they going to have
a civil rights movement?

00:29:00.100 --> 00:29:03.050
Maybe-- because in
the future, robots

00:29:03.050 --> 00:29:07.060
may be programmed to feel pain.

00:29:07.060 --> 00:29:10.880
Today, we feel pain
because it's good for us.

00:29:10.880 --> 00:29:15.700
Otherwise, we lose our fingers,
our fingers get burned, cut up.

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:18.790
Pain is good, because
it prevents us

00:29:18.790 --> 00:29:21.280
from destroying ourselves.

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:24.900
Eventually, robots
may have to feel pain.

00:29:24.900 --> 00:29:28.180
Otherwise, we will tell
them to jump off a cliff,

00:29:28.180 --> 00:29:30.080
and they'll destroy themselves.

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:31.540
They have to feel pain.

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:34.070
At that point, it
has to be regulated.

00:29:34.070 --> 00:29:37.120
So we may have a robots
civil rights movement

00:29:37.120 --> 00:29:41.170
to limit the amount of
pain that a master can

00:29:41.170 --> 00:29:44.350
impose upon their robot.

00:29:44.350 --> 00:29:47.080
Now that of course is
many, many decades away.

00:29:47.080 --> 00:29:49.210
But eventually,
robots may also be

00:29:49.210 --> 00:29:53.020
part of our ethical
understanding of technology

00:29:53.020 --> 00:29:56.320
when they feel pain.

00:29:56.320 --> 00:29:57.490
TAYLOR WILSON: Interesting.

00:29:57.490 --> 00:29:59.260
All right over here.

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:02.390
MICHIO KAKU: Dr. Kaku, one
of my earliest memories

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:04.270
is of watching the
Discovery Channel

00:30:04.270 --> 00:30:06.260
and seeing you on there.

00:30:06.260 --> 00:30:07.900
Thank you for the
role that you played

00:30:07.900 --> 00:30:09.880
in shaping that part of my
early childhood experience.

00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:10.930
MICHIO KAKU: Thank you.

00:30:10.930 --> 00:30:12.820
AUDIENCE: And related
to that, I wanted

00:30:12.820 --> 00:30:15.790
to hear what you are
excited about when it comes

00:30:15.790 --> 00:30:19.060
to expanding the scale and
accessibility of science

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:20.350
communication into the future.

00:30:23.310 --> 00:30:27.180
MICHIO KAKU: Well, it used to be
that mass media would stay away

00:30:27.180 --> 00:30:31.320
from science because, quote,
"Science doesn't sell."

00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:35.480
so back in those days we
only had three networks

00:30:35.480 --> 00:30:39.930
and science was invisible
for the most part.

00:30:39.930 --> 00:30:42.240
And most people, when they
learned about science,

00:30:42.240 --> 00:30:44.890
they learned about
science in school.

00:30:44.890 --> 00:30:46.590
But there's a problem there.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:49.260
First of all, we're
all born scientists.

00:30:49.260 --> 00:30:52.620
When we're born, we want
to know why the sun shines.

00:30:52.620 --> 00:30:54.430
We better know
where we came from.

00:30:54.430 --> 00:30:58.350
But then we hit
the greatest killer

00:30:58.350 --> 00:31:01.590
of scientists known to science.

00:31:01.590 --> 00:31:05.550
The greatest destroyer of
scientists known to science

00:31:05.550 --> 00:31:10.430
is junior high school.

00:31:10.430 --> 00:31:13.310
When we hit junior high
school, it's all over.

00:31:13.310 --> 00:31:17.240
We lose scientists by the
hundreds of thousands.

00:31:17.240 --> 00:31:17.960
Why?

00:31:17.960 --> 00:31:20.530
Because science is made boring.

00:31:20.530 --> 00:31:22.250
It's made repetitive.

00:31:22.250 --> 00:31:25.880
You have to learn to
name things rather than

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:30.390
learning the great principles,
the great concepts of science.

00:31:30.390 --> 00:31:32.970
And that's why more recently
we have the internet,

00:31:32.970 --> 00:31:37.290
we have cable, which brings
science to an audience.

00:31:37.290 --> 00:31:41.120
Now it turns out that about
a million people subscribe

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:43.640
to "Scientific American".

00:31:43.640 --> 00:31:45.500
That's the hard core.

00:31:45.500 --> 00:31:48.500
These people will
seek out science even

00:31:48.500 --> 00:31:52.160
when there's no science, about
a million people, the hardcore.

00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:55.310
But then there's another
5 to 10 million people

00:31:55.310 --> 00:31:59.030
who will tune in
sometimes to Discovery,

00:31:59.030 --> 00:32:01.400
Science Channel,
National Geographic,

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:04.460
if there's something really
interesting happening.

00:32:04.460 --> 00:32:08.360
So we know that we can
reach 5 to 10 million people

00:32:08.360 --> 00:32:10.340
on a good program.

00:32:10.340 --> 00:32:13.790
And then with the discovery
of the black hole,

00:32:13.790 --> 00:32:18.410
we can reach 100 million
people when we reach resonance,

00:32:18.410 --> 00:32:21.240
we resonate with the
people of the world.

00:32:21.240 --> 00:32:24.890
So we need more people
to write books, more

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:28.250
people to be on television,
to do radio shows.

00:32:28.250 --> 00:32:31.850
We need more people like
that, rather than less people,

00:32:31.850 --> 00:32:38.420
to become role models for a
new scientific revolution.

00:32:38.420 --> 00:32:39.360
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:43.450
TAYLOR WILSON: Definitely,
that's great advice.

00:32:43.450 --> 00:32:43.950
All right.

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:44.450
Up here?

00:32:44.450 --> 00:32:46.183
AUDIENCE: Thanks sir.

00:32:46.183 --> 00:32:47.350
Thanks for coming out today.

00:32:47.350 --> 00:32:51.130
I was wondering your thoughts on
NASA's recently announced plan

00:32:51.130 --> 00:32:53.620
to return to the moon in 2024.

00:32:53.620 --> 00:32:55.713
Do you think it's feasible?

00:32:55.713 --> 00:32:57.130
MICHIO KAKU: First
of all, I think

00:32:57.130 --> 00:33:02.440
we're going to have a traffic
jam around the moon very soon.

00:33:02.440 --> 00:33:07.180
First, NASA has the
SLS booster rocket.

00:33:07.180 --> 00:33:11.140
Next year, we'll
orbit around the moon.

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:16.450
Then we have Elon Musk of
SpaceX who's selling tickets--

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:19.030
tickets to the general public.

00:33:19.030 --> 00:33:20.410
He's been sold out.

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:24.100
A Japanese billionaire
bought out the entire tickets

00:33:24.100 --> 00:33:27.460
for the Falcon Heavy
rocket that is also

00:33:27.460 --> 00:33:30.910
fully capable of
going around the moon.

00:33:30.910 --> 00:33:35.230
And then we have Jeff Bezos of
Amazon, formerly the richest

00:33:35.230 --> 00:33:36.830
man in the world.

00:33:36.830 --> 00:33:41.500
He has a whole spaceport,
the Blue Origins rocket

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:46.900
program to go to the moon with
the Neil Armstrong rocket.

00:33:46.900 --> 00:33:49.265
And then we have the Chinese.

00:33:49.265 --> 00:33:50.890
The Chinese have
announced that they're

00:33:50.890 --> 00:33:54.550
going to plant the
Chinese flag on the moon.

00:33:54.550 --> 00:33:57.700
So I think we're going to
have a traffic jam with three

00:33:57.700 --> 00:34:02.740
American rockets, one Chinese,
and perhaps one European rocket

00:34:02.740 --> 00:34:05.620
fully committed to
go back to the moon.

00:34:05.620 --> 00:34:07.960
And the question is, why?

00:34:07.960 --> 00:34:11.050
Because costs have
been dropping.

00:34:11.050 --> 00:34:13.520
Technology is catching up.

00:34:13.520 --> 00:34:15.530
You realize that
your cell phone--

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:20.199
your cell phone has more
computer power than all of NASA

00:34:20.199 --> 00:34:24.978
in 1969 when we put
two men on the moon.

00:34:24.978 --> 00:34:25.520
That's right.

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:28.330
Your cell phone today
has more computer power

00:34:28.330 --> 00:34:29.920
than all of NASA.

00:34:29.920 --> 00:34:31.870
In fact, I think
it's criminal what

00:34:31.870 --> 00:34:35.380
they were doing in 1969,
criminal sending humans

00:34:35.380 --> 00:34:38.500
into space backed up
by one cell phone.

00:34:38.500 --> 00:34:41.710
Would you go into outer space
knowing that your rocket is

00:34:41.710 --> 00:34:44.120
backed up by one cell phone?

00:34:44.120 --> 00:34:46.110
That's what we did in 1969.

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:47.656
I think it's criminal.

00:34:47.656 --> 00:34:49.239
So I think that we're
going to witness

00:34:49.239 --> 00:34:53.050
a second golden era
of space exploration

00:34:53.050 --> 00:34:57.930
as costs begin to drop,
not $10,000 a pound,

00:34:57.930 --> 00:35:00.790
not even $1,000 a
pound, but eventually,

00:35:00.790 --> 00:35:03.200
a few hundred dollars per pound.

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:05.600
That's the goal.

00:35:05.600 --> 00:35:06.350
TAYLOR WILSON: Oh.

00:35:06.350 --> 00:35:06.892
That's great.

00:35:06.892 --> 00:35:08.920
